## Code Review Goals

Back while I was in high school I decided I wanted to write a game engine, so my friend David and I started out in 2012. Despite game engines typically being written in C or C++, we decided to write the engine in Java as we were both familiar with it.  After 10,000 lines of code I had something I could loosely call a game engine. I am still very proud of what I achieved, but in many ways the &quot;Illumination Engine&quot; (the name might be a little cringe worthy) was a failure. Probably in more ways than it was a success. I still learned a huge amount about architecture and project management from the time I spent working on it. However, I really can&#39;t isolate a lot of the failed design choices.  Now, in 2016, I am writing a new graphics engine (with a smaller scope – illumination engine was intended to do physics, audio, and graphics) and I realized that there&#39;s probably a lot I could learn by going over the entirety of illumination and evaluating the decisions I made when designing the engine. I hope to apply knowledge my new project. I also believe the process of reflecting on my old code will help me appreciate my development as a programmer.

## Pre-requisite Materials

If you want to follow along with this series of posts, you&#39;ll probably need to have some experience with OpenGL and 3D graphics. I&#39;m probably not going to explain a lot of the API or theory behind rendering. Besides that, it will probably be helpful to have the [Bitbucket Repository for Illumination](https://bitbucket.org/Spaceman42/illumination/src) open. The repository has a couple of projects (not all of which I worked on), but I&#39;ll mainly be in the &quot;Illumination Engine&quot; project. One thing to note is that the engine does not run any more... I'll dig up some old screen shots to prove that it actually worked for my next post. It seems there's a problem with some of the shaders (which isn't totally surprising... they are pretty poorly written).

## Part 1:

This post is mostly going to cover the abstract design of the engine. In the next post I&#39;ll start getting into implementation details.

## Illumination Engine Goals

Before evaluating the engine, it&#39;s important to understand its intended purpose. Illumination was intended to be a full &quot;game engine.&quot; The engine was written in Java and used LWJGL to access native libraries like OpenGL. It was supposed to be able to handle graphics (using OpenGL 4), audio (using OpenAL), physics (using a custom physics library), and input (using LWJGLs) bindings (I&#39;m not actually sure what LWJGL uses…). The only component that was ever actually &quot;finished&quot; was the graphics component. This was the part of the engine that I was most interested in and ended up being what I worked on the most. We did however integrate bullet physics when it became apparent writing our own physics engine would be impractical.

As far as the renderer goes, Illumination was intended to be a &quot;generalized renderer&quot; – it was supposed to support as many different configurations and scenes as possible. The overall goal was to have a renderer so scalable that we could add or remove effects easily without making _any_ changes to the rest of the engine. That is, rendering engine where different features were completely decoupled from each other. At the time, this goal seemed fairly achievable, but we quickly realized how difficult it would be. In fact, I am still not sure how possible it is. Regardless, when designing the engine we decided we would target a (we thought) small subset of features. These were

- Multiple dynamic lights
  - Point lights
  - Directional lights
  - Spot lights
- Real Time Shadow Mapping for Spot and Directional Lights
- Screen Space Ambient Occlusion (SSAO)
- Antialiasing
- Normal Mapping
- Bloom
- HDR lighting (eye adaption)
- Depth of field

Now, let&#39;s look into the high level architecture we designed to achieve this:

## Diving into the High Level Design

At the most basic level Illumination is a deferred renderer. That is, it decouples lighting with the rendering of geometry. We chose deferred rendering because it both allowed for both a high number of dynamic lights and it allows for the lighting model to be changed without significant work.  Deferred rendering also allows for the easy addition of post-processes which helped satisfy the requirement of a decoupled renderer.

The engine compiles as a library which can then be included with a game. The game (the &quot;user&#39;s code&quot;) is able to access engine functionality by instantiating the engine and extending several of the engine classes. This aspect of the design worked fairly well, though there where some issues with static vs instance variables and methods in the engine, which I&#39;ll get into more when going through the actual code.

That&#39;s all well and good, but how was the engine actually structured?

### Project Structure

The engine is broken into 7 major packages. They are:

- Asset
  - Handles the loading of assets (3d models, and textures) and their storage during runtime
- Game
  - Handles the scene graph and has the abstract objects that ought to be extended by the Game module to run
- Graphics
  - Handles the actually rendering
- Gui
  - Handles the gui – this package is a mess
- Io
  - Handles keyboard and mouse input
- Math
  - All the basic math functions
- Request
  - Handles the communications between threads.

There is also a physics and an audio package, but that is outside the scope of this review.

### Runtime

Illumination is a multithreaded engine with (excluding physics) two primary threads: the render thread and the game thread. The game thread is where the user&#39;s code is run. While the user is not explicitly limited to using only the one thread, there is no support in the engine for multithreaded game processing, so implementing that would be up to the user. The render thread maintains the OpenGL context and handles rendering (as the name implies). I think this basic design is… okay, but it has a couple problems. The process of communicating between threads was intended to have as little blocking as physically possible. Having two &#39;uberthreads&quot; that handle all processing is somewhat limiting and lacks scalability. In modern engines, rendering is broken up between multiple threads, even if only one thread submits draw calls to OpenGL. This allows the computation heavy work of computing object&#39;s transformation matrices and animation to be split up between threads. It also acts to decouple the renderer from the actual api, which is something that became very difficult in Illumination (though there were other factors for this as well).

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Basic structure of the engine at runtime. (Can&#39;t go wrong with crappy paint graphics)

Both threads had virtually independent loops. The game loops sends completed frames to the renderer as soon as it finishes them. Illumination is gernally &quot;optimistic&quot; when it comes to threading, meaning it doesn&#39;t do a lot of checking to make sure every thread is synchronized. This ideology is more visible in the design of the &quot;Request&quot; system which I will get to later. This was intended to separate game processing completely from rendering, but the solution had some flaws. First, if either loop got too far ahead of the other there could be problems. Early in development there were flickering problems as the render loop would not block when there was no frame to render and would just display a black screen. This was fixed by caching the data from the last received frame on the rendering thread, which was acceptable if not the most elegant solution.  The actual implementation this subsystem is also iffy at best. While some sort of frame queue might have made sense (that&#39;s even what I thought the engine used) the engine doesn&#39;t use one. Instead, the game thread just copies a List&lt;RenderableObjects&gt; and a Camera over to the render thread. I think a better architecture here would be to have a rendering command queue that is built during the game loop. This rendering command queue could then be consumed by the OpenGL thread to render objects. This could be multithreaded by allowing computing the next frame while the rendering thread consumes the command queue for the current frame. This would dramatically simplify communication between the OpenGL context and the game and it would also reduce the complexity of each component.

The next important component to review from a high level is the Request system. This is where the design of the engine becomes somewhat complicated and significantly more difficult to manage. In order to break this down, I&#39;m going to go step by step through what happens when the user&#39;s code wants to load a model:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. Game Thread sends an IORequest to the thread manager asking for an asset to be loaded from the disk. ThreadManager immediately returns an empty class representing that asset to game (Remember, no blocking).
2. ThreadManager dispatches the request to the AssetManager (only really exists in concept).
3.  Asset manager starts a thread to load the asset from the disk
4. When the asset is loaded from the disk, the thread sends a GLRequest to ThreadManager to load the asset into VRAM
5. ThreadManager dispatches the request to the RenderThread, which handles the request before starting to render the next frame
6. The render thread updates the asset class in the game thread with all the data that was just loaded

This system was a complete mess. I still think that the general idea behind was fine, but the implementation was messy, possibley due to the two threaded structure of the engine. From a design perspective, it becomes very difficult to follow what sending a request actually does, making the code difficult to debug. A lot of problems arose from the fact that the request returned an empty object of the type request. I.E. the users asks to load a mesh, so they make an IOMeshLoadRequest. This immediately returns a Mesh object to them, just without any data. After the data is loaded, the user can start using the mesh. If the request instead returned a hypothetical &quot;MeshPrototype&quot; object which could be used to construct an actual mesh after the data was loaded, the system would be much less error prone and easier to follow. There were also major problems in the implantation of this design that made it much more difficult then it needed to be – more on that in future posts.

## Part 1 Conclusions

Illumination had a messy design that made it hard to manage as the engine became more complicated. A lot of the basic ideas behind the design of components were good, but the components weren&#39;t really design with each other in mind, which led to extremely complex interactions in some cases. The design of having two main threads also led to many problems and probably didn&#39;t have any substantial performance benefits because most of the computation remained on one thread (the rendering thread). A better solution would have been to have multiple threads build a command queue that is consumed by a rendering thread. I&#39;m pretty sure this would allow for high performance and more flexible threading while also reducing the complexity of the engine.

In Part 2 I&#39;ll start diving into the actual code. The code is pretty tightly coupled (unfortunately) which might make my plan of going component by component somewhat difficult.
